1.2 Data set requirements

The above data set meets

  • the response variable must be continuous random variables.
    • There are continuous random variables that we can use in this data set as our response variable based on the question we are asking. In this case the response variable we are looking at is bmi.
  • at least two categorical explanatory variables
    • There are at least two categorical explanatory variables in this data set. The first one is gender and the second one is smoking_history.
  • at least one of the categorical variables has more than two categories.
    • The variable smoking_history has more than two categories.
  • at least two numerical explanatory variables.
    • There are at least two numerical explanatory variables, one is age and another in bmi, however there are several more.
  • at least 15 observations are required for estimating each regression coefficient. For example, if your final linear model has 11 variables (including dummy variables), you need \(12 \times 15 = 180\) observations.
    • There are 100,000 observations in this data set and only 9 variables so we have surpassed the required amount of observations.

2 Part 2

2.1 Introduction

2.2 Materials

This assignment is going to look at diabetic prediction data. While there is no specific context regarding the collection of the data, the synopsis explains that the data set is a collection of demographic and medical data from patients. The data set has 100000 observations and 9 variables which are as followed,

gender: chr age: num hypertension: int heart_disease: int smoking_history: chr bmi: num HbA1c_level: num blood_glucose_level: int diabetes: int

A practical question to look into with this data set would be is there an observable relationship between any of these variables. An analytical question for this data set would be is it possible to use the relationships of those variables to predict one another without the use of the diabetes variable.

While the data set is smaller in terms of variables there are plenty of observations that is likely that we have enough information to answer the questions about the data set.

2.3 Methodolgy and Analysis

Age is the response variable with the best linear relationship to BMI. While the scatterplot does depict some outliers, if you were to ignore them and condence the viewing screen of the scatterplot it would be clear there is a strong linear relationship between the variables.

Looking at the least square regression model for the variables we can see that BMI = 2.316e+01 + age*9.945e-02.

plot(model)

Looking at the first plot, Residuals vs. Fit, due to the sheer number of observations in the data it does not seem like there is any form of clustering but instead one large data cluster. Looking at the Q-Q Residuals plot it appears to have a strong linear depiction right up until the 2 mark where we see it have a drastic increase in slope. The Scale-Location chart depicts the same issue as the Residuals vs Fit, due to the sheer amount of observations it appears to be one giant cluster. Finally the Residuals vs Leverage plot appears to have clusters in the forms of vertical bars of data, everything is almost perfectly vertical in its respective column on this plot. The use of the bootstrap procedure should help improve the fit of the linear regression model. Considering the incredibly large amount of observations in the data set, the bootstrapping method tends to yield similar results to the parametric methods.

2.3.2 Bootstrapping

D <- 1000

boot.beta0 <- NULL 
boot.beta1 <- NULL
## bootstrap regression models using for-loop
vec.id <- 1:length(BMI)   # vector of observation ID
for(i in 1:D){
  boot.id <- sample(vec.id, length(BMI), replace = TRUE)   # bootstrap obs ID.
  boot.BMI <- BMI[boot.id]           # bootstrap bmi
  boot.Age <- Age[boot.id]     # corresponding bootstrap age

  boot.reg <-lm(BMI[boot.id] ~ Age[boot.id]) 
  boot.beta0[i] <- coef(boot.reg)[1]  
  boot.beta1[i] <- coef(boot.reg)[2]}
boot.beta0.ci <- quantile(boot.beta0, c(0.025, 0.975), type = 2)
boot.beta1.ci <- quantile(boot.beta1, c(0.025, 0.975), type = 2)
boot.coef <- data.frame(rbind(boot.beta0.ci, boot.beta1.ci)) 
names(boot.coef) <- c("2.5%", "97.5%")

kable(boot.coef, caption = "95% Confidence Interval for Bootstrapped Regression")
95% Confidence Interval for Bootstrapped Regression
2.5% 97.5%
boot.beta0.ci 23.0762366 23.2392767
boot.beta1.ci 0.0977904 0.1010721

2.4 Results and Conclusions

The final regression model is BMI = 2.316e+01 + age*9.945e-02 with 95% Bootstrap CI (0.0977646, 0.1011631). The model indicates a negative relationship between BMI and age. Additionally, the confidence interval does not include 0, which indicates there being a statistical correlation between the two variables. Since the data set is significantly large there is minimal difference between the bootstrap and parametric methods. However, considering the size of the data set, it brings into question the quality of the data set and thus the quality of the results. The best solution is to rerun everything with a significantly smaller sample of the data set and interpret those results to have the best conclusion.

2.5 General Discussions

It is clear now that after running the tests with this data set, that this data set was less than ideal for these tasks. With both being so large and also having most of the numerical response variables actually being integers this data set there were limited variables that would have created a good linear relationship to analyze, even with transformation. Moving forward using a data set with significantly less observations and less integer numeric variables would be best suited for this method and would yield better results. The sheer amount of observations made the graphs difficult to read and made it hard to properly interpret the data. For future use of this large data set it might be more beneficial to use it as a population and take a random sample from the population to analyze as its own data set, that way the data is a more manageable size.
